We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the 

(a) Accounting Office to (i) use the prescribed accounting procedures for inventories; 

(ii) provide the above-identified lacking documents and information; 

(iii) ensure future disbursements are adequately documented; and 

(iv) withhold the proper amount of taxes from each supplier; and 

(b) BAC Secretariat to post the required procurement data for all emergency purchases under the R.A. No. 11469 to promote transparency and accountability.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to 

(a) advise the Local Development Council (LDC) to (i) exercise due diligence in the review of the budget to ensure the proper funding source of projects for optimum utilization of government funds; and 

(ii) together with the Municipal Engineering Office, consider in planning as much as possible all factors that may affect the timely implementation of PPAs; 

(b) direct the BAC members to schedule procurement of all PPAs in a manner that would allow timely implementation of the projects; 

(c) require the Municipal Engineering Office to conduct regular monitoring of project implementation; and 

(d) instruct the BAC and the Municipal Accountant to submit all the disbursement vouchers and provide the lacking documents and information, and henceforth ensure completeness of documents supporting the use of the fund.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to 

(a) request the SB to enact resolution or ordinance adopting the new SWMP; 

(b) instruct the MSWMB to (i) involve closely all the Barangay Officials in the strict implementation of the existing environmental laws and the SWMP, once legislated and approved; 

(ii) strengthen the Information and Education Campaign (IEC) especially on “proper waste segregation” and “yes segregation, yes collection policy” among citizens; and 

(iii) monitor the operations of the municipal ecological waste center and RCA to avoid the accumulation and holding of waste for extended period; 

(c) prioritize the registration of the mini dump truck to maximize its utilization; and 

(d) require the immediate replacement of the dump truck procured.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the 

(a) HRMO to (i) facilitate the filling up of the vacant position in the LDRRMO;  and 

(ii) ensure that JO personnel do not perform the duties of a regular employee; 

(b) Accounting Office to transfer to STF the appropriate amount of unexpended balance of LDDRMF; 

(c) LDRRMC to ensure that only eligible PPAs are budgeted; 

(d) BAC to conduct timely procurement activities of DRRM projects; and 

(e) LDRRMO to (i) see to it that projects are timely implemented; and 

(ii) submit the report on sources and utilization of DRRMF within the prescribed period.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) cause the preparation of a balanced budget for 20% Development Plan so that other areas of concern, such as social development, economic development and environmental management may be given equal attention by the Municipal Government; 

(b) ensure that the Local Development Council (LDC) and the Municipal Engineering Office properly plan and schedule all procurement activities in a manner that would allow timely implementation of the projects; 

(c) advice the LDC to ensure that the development projects charged to 20% DF are qualified under DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No.2017-1; and 

(d) instruct the BAC and the Municipal Accountant to provide the Audit Team with the lacking documents and information, and henceforth ensure completeness of documents supporting the use of the fund.

We recommended and Management agreed to 

(a) fully adhere with the provisions under the said JMC; 

(b) exert more effort in complying the Minimum Standards on Disaster Risk Reduction and Management, specifically in terms of service delivery and equipage; 

(c) submission of the lacking sales invoice is required as well as the submission of the Disbursement Vouchers; and 


(d) continue the good work and performance started in disaster preparedness and risk reduction management.

